;\n\n\n\t\tdata <= 0;\n\t\tdata[256] <= 1\'b1;\n\t\tload <= 1;\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\tload <= 0;\n\t\trepeat(1000) @(posedge clk) begin\n\t\tend\n\t\tdata <= 512\'h1000000000000001;\n\t\tload <= 1;\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\tload <= 0;\n\t\trepeat(1000) @(posedge clk) begin\n\t\tend\n\n\t\tdata <= $random;\n\t\tload <= 1;\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\tload <= 0;\n\t\trepeat(1000) @(posedge clk) begin\n\t\tend\n\n\t\tdata <= 0;\n\t\tload <= 1;\n\t\trepeat(20) @(posedge clk);\n\t\trepeat(2) @(posedge clk) data <= data + 2;\n\t\t@(posedge clk) begin \n\t\t\tload <= 0;\n\t\t\tdata <= data + 1;\n\t\tend\n\t\trepeat(20) @(posedge clk) data <= data + 1;\n\t\trepeat(500) @(posedge clk) begin\n\t\tend\n\n\t\t#1 $finish;\n\tend\n\t\nendmodule\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_q;\n\t\tint errortime_q;\n\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t\n\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\n\twire wavedrom_enable;\n\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\n\t\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\tlogic load;\n\tlogic [511:0] data;\n\tlogic [511:0] q_ref;\n\tlogic [511:0] q_dut;\n\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, stim1.clk, tb_mismatch ,clk,load,data,q_ref,q_dut );\n\tend\n\n\n\twire tb_match;\t\t// Verification\n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.* ,\n\t\t.load,\n\t\t.data );\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.load,\n\t\t.data,\n\t\t.q(q_ref) );\n\t\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.clk,\n\t\t.load,\n\t\t.data,\n\t\t.q(q_dut) );\n\n\t\n\tbit strobe = 0;\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // Try to delay until the very end of the time step.\n\t\t\t@(strobe);\n\t\tend\n\tendtask\t\n\n\t\n\tfinal begin\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_q) $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has %0d mismatches. First mismatch occurred at time %0d.", "q", stats1.errors_q, stats1.errortime_q);\n\t\telse $display("Hint: Output \'%s\' has no mismatches.", "q");\n\n\t\t$display("Hint: Total mismatched samples is %1d out of %1d samples\\n", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\t\t$display("Simulation finished at %0d ps", $time);\n\t\t$display("Mismatches: %1d in %1d samples", stats1.errors, stats1.clocks);\n\tend\n\t\n\t// Verification: XORs on the right makes any X in good_vector match anything, but X in dut_vector will only match X.\n\tassign tb_match = ( { q_ref } === ( { q_ref } ^ { q_dut } ^ { q_ref } ) );\n\t// Use explicit sensitivity list here. @(*) causes NetProc::nex_input() to be called when trying to compute\n\t// the sensitivity list of the @(strobe) process, which isn\'t implemented.\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\t\tif (!tb_match) begin\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) stats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors++;\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (q_ref !== ( q_ref ^ q_dut ^ q_ref ))\n\t\tbegin if (stats1.errors_q == 0) stats1.errortime_q = $time;\n\t\t\tstats1.errors_q = stats1.errors_q+1\'b1; end\n\n\tend\n\n   // add timeout after 100K cycles\n   initial begin\n     #1000000\n     $display("TIMEOUT");\n     $finish();\n   end\n\nendmodule\n\n\n<golden_testbench>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.ASSISTANT: 'assistant'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='{\n    "reasoning": "The user requires three main tasks: 1) Create an IO interface matching the specification derived from the golden testbench, 2) Improve the provided golden testbench to meet specific display requirements, and 3) Ensure the final testbench adheres to all constraints.\\n\\n**Interface Derivation:**\\n1. The `input_spec` defines `TopModule` with ports: `clk` (input, 1 bit), `load` (input, 1 bit), `data` (input, 512 bits), `q` (output, 512 bits).\\n2. The `golden_testbench` instantiates `TopModule` as `top_module1` with the exact ports specified: `.clk, .load, .data, .q(q_dut)`.\\n3. The `golden_testbench` also uses `stimulus_gen` which has extra ports (`wavedrom_title`, `wavedrom_enable`). Since the interface requested is *for the module* being tested (`TopModule`), I will stick to the `TopModule` interface derived from the spec/instantiation, but I must also account for the context of the provided testbench structure.\\n4. The request states: \'The module interface should EXACTLY MATCH the description in input_spec.\' and \'Generate interface according to golden testbench, even if it contradicts the input_spec.\' Since the golden testbench is complex and relies on `stimulus_gen`, I will define the interface for `TopModule` based on the `input_spec` as requested for the module itself, but I will need to modify the testbench heavily to incorporate the new display requirements and keep the original functionality.\\n\\n**Testbench Improvement:**\\n1. **Functionality Maintenance:** All original logic (error counting, timing, task usage, module instantiation) must be kept.\\n2. **Golden Testbench Contradiction:** The golden testbench defines error counting logic in the `tb` module. I must enhance this logic to include detailed display upon the first mismatch.\\n3. **New Display Requirements:**\\n    a. When a mismatch occurs, display input signals, output signals, and expected output signals at that time.\\n    b. For multi-bit signals (512 bits here), display in HEX and BINARY format if width <= 64 bits. (Since 512 bits > 64 bits, I will only display HEX for 512-bit signals unless the comparison logic forces a smaller view). The rule states "\n    , \n    ". Since 512 bits > 64 bits, I will focus on HEX output for the full 512-bit signals.\\n    c. Final summary must be: \\"SIMULATION PASSED\\" or \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\".\\n\\n**Implementation Steps:**\\n1. **Interface:** Define the `TopModule` interface strictly as per `input_spec`.\\n2. **Testbench Modification:**\\n    a. Introduce logic to capture and display signals (`clk`, `load`, `data`, `q_ref`, `q_dut`) when `tb_mismatch` is true and `stats1.errors == 1`.\\n    b. Modify the `final` block to output the required success/failure message based on `stats1.errors`.\\n    c. Handle the display formatting (HEX/BIN).\\n\\n**Advice to Avoid Syntax Errors:**\\n1. Use `logic` data types for signal connections in the testbench to handle mixed use as registers/wires, which is modern SystemVerilog practice.\\n2. Ensure all module definitions (`module ... endmodule`) are complete.\\n3. Carefully manage the scope of variables, especially those used for error tracking (`stats1`).\\n\\n**Conflict Resolution:** The testbench relies on `stimulus_gen`, `RefModule`, and `TopModule`. Since I am only asked to provide the interface and the testbench, I must assume `TopModule`, `RefModule`, and `stimulus_gen` are defined elsewhere or provide placeholder definitions if they are essential for compilation. Given the structure, I will only define the required interface for `TopModule` and augment the testbench structure, assuming placeholders for missing modules.\\n\\n**Signal Display Logic:** For 512-bit signals, I will use `$display` formatting for HEX and mention the binary representation is too large to display inline, fulfilling the spirit of the requirement for multi-bit signals.\\n\\n**Final Check:** The required failure message format is: \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\". The success message is: \\"SIMULATION PASSED\\". I will implement this in the `final` block, replacing the existing `Hint:` displays.\\n\\n*Self-Correction on Display:* The original testbench calculates mismatch using: `assign tb_match = ( { q_ref } === ( { q_ref } ^ { q_dut } ^ { q_ref } ) );`. This simplifies to `tb_match = ( { q_ref } === { q_dut } )`, because $A \\text{ XOR } A = 0$, so $Q_{ref} \\text{ XOR } Q_{dut} \\text{ XOR } Q_{ref} = Q_{dut}$. Therefore, the check is simply $Q_{ref} == Q_{dut}$. The original error counting logic is preserved, but